""" So what was given to us was the synonyms empty dictionary and we were told to get 2 inputs.
One was to get a word of the txt file that the individual wanted to access. The other was to 
get the synonyms of that word from the first input, for the letter that was input second.
I tried to make it simple and straight forward and ended up going in a round about way that
worked in the end.
"""
synonyms = {}   # Define dictionary
contents = []
easy_list = []
stripped_list = []

""" input word -> word.txt, read the file, pulled the file contents, made a list, broke it down
into a nested list, flattened it out, committed every word to the dictionary with it's first
letter being the key (that was a hint from the instructions). The second input is a letter,
pulled the values using the letter as the key. Printed the values. If no key matched the letter
then it prints No Synonyms for that word exist for the letter. I think the only best practice
item that should have been changed before submitting was not having "word" in two or three
different spots, loops, etc. I thought it could be cleaner code though much like how I did
the easy_list. It would just make some lines longer.
"""

word_input = input()
let_input = input()
file1 = word_input + ".txt"
openfile = open(file1, "r")
for line in openfile.readlines():
    contents.append(line.split(" "))
easy_list = [item for sublist in contents for item in sublist]
stripped_list = [s.strip() for s in easy_list]
for word in stripped_list:
    letter = word[0]
    if letter not in synonyms:
        synonyms[letter] = []
    synonyms[letter].append(word)
if let_input in synonyms:
    for word in synonyms[let_input]:
        print(word)
else:
    print(f"No synonyms for {word_input} begin with {let_input}.")
